    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n5999" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέγας, μεγάλη, μέγα</span></b> , comp.
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μείζων</span>, sup. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέγιστος</span>: <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">great, large</span>, of persons,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">tall</span> (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κᾱλός τε μέγας τε, κᾱλή
            τε μεγάλη τε, Φ 108</span>, <i><span class="en">Od.
            15.418</span></i>); of things with reference to any kind of dimension,
          and also to power, loudness, etc., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἄνεμος</span>, 
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἰαχή, ὀρυμαγδός</span>; in unfavorable sense,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέγα ἔργον</span> (facinus), so <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέγα ἔπος, μέγα φρονεῖν, εἰπεῖν</span>, ‘be proud,’
          ‘boast,’ <i><span class="en">Od. 3.261</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Od. 22.288</span></i>.—Adv., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μεγάλως</span>, also <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέγα,
            μεγάλα</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">greatly, exceedingly, aloud</span>,
          etc.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
</div>